animal.description:
Look at this gorgeous girl! Say hello to Kiera! <3

"I think Kiera was an outside dog. She's shy when she meets people. She's sweet but doesn't want to be touched. We are working on trust, so she will enjoy petting and back rubs. Kiera hasn't had any accidents in the house. She sleeps a lot. Acts like she hasn't been inside a house very often so is timid about exploring it inside. It's been rewarding watching her heal. She's gaining weight. Her skin is healing and her hair is growing back.
Kiera was more active when Burl Ives was here. She tried engaging him in play, bouncing and zooming around him. That was a joy to watch."

Kiera is a gorgeous girl who hasn't had the best life. She was rescued by OAA after it was reported that some dogs were living alone on a property. Their owner had fallen ill and was in the hospital and there was no one else around to care for them. When they reached out to us about intaking this girl, we knew she would soon be part of our fluffy butt family! 

Kiera is a 10 year old female Great Pyrenees/Golden Retriever mix. She currently weighs about 64lbs, but is still on the thin side. She came to us with a lot of hair loss, but thanks to loving care of her foster it has been coming back in nicely. Kiera is happy when meeting new people, but also a bit shy. She wants to be social, but at the same time can be reserved. Kiera has not been to any public outings, but given her age and personality she is probably more of a homebody. Her personality is calm and laid back. Kiera has excellent house manners, and can be given free roam of the house. Kiera has not shown to be a big chewer in her foster home. She hasn't been super vocal, but she does bark if there is reason too. 

Kiera is uninterested in playing fetch. We are unsure if she is a water dog or not. Kiera does sometimes play with toys. She seems to be slowly figuring out what they are. Kiera has not shown to have any food aggression or resource guarding in her foster home. Kiera doesn't seem to be a big hugger and doesn't jump on people. Kiera walks okay on a leash, but could use some more working with. Kiera does currently get car sick. We are unsure how Kiera would do in an apartment setting. When no one is home or at night, she stays in the sunroom and does great! Kiera is potty trained, but is NOT kennel trained. 

Kiera is your typical senior. She is calmer, she is low maintenance and a total sweetheart once she settles in. She has started prancing around like a puppy at times, and it is the cutest thing ever! If you are interested in this beauty, here are some things to note

-Kiera is shy around other dogs. She mostly keeps to herself. However, she is in love with the foster puppies her foster currently has. She is even playful with them at times. 

-Kiera is good with cats.

-Kiera has not been around any kids. Given her age, they should be older. She probably can't handle the energy of a toddler, but would probably love the attention from an older kiddo. 

-Kiera is being fostered in Sand Springs, OK. We do ask her adoptive family be able to pick her up in person, even if they are out of state. 

Kiera isn't really looking for much in her new home. She is looking for a calmer home environment. One that has lots of love to give, but also knows she is an older gal and sometimes likes her peace. If you want to spoil this girl through her golden years, then please apply to adopt her at https://www.pyrpawsandfluffytailsrescue.com/adoption-app

Her adoption fee is $150. That will include her DHLPP, Rabies, and Bordatella. She will also have bloodwork done and be spayed. She will be heart-worm and ehrlicia negative, and be current on her preventatives. She will also be micro-chipped.

Puppies and other highly-adoptable dogs (small dogs or desirable-breed dogs) at PPA! are very high in demand and usually have several interested adopters. Inquiring about a dog, meeting a dog, and even applying for a dog does not guarantee that you will be able to adopt the dog. 

Only one household will be able to adopt each dog, which means all other interested households will inevitably and unfortunately be disappointed. Please consider this in your search and set your expectations accordingly. Please also consider that adult dogs do not typically have competing adopters, and they need forever homes, too! 

PPA! does not allow the adoption of dogs who are related (e.g., littermates or mom and pup) to the same household for behavioral reasons.

Please complete our information sheet for adoption (https://pflugervillepetsalive.org/ppaforms/PPADogAdoptionInformationSheet.pdf) and return it to us, the adoption team adopt@pflugervillepetsalive.org. Because there may be other interested adopters, it is in your best interest to submit your information sheet and schedule a meet and greet as soon as possible.

PUPPIES AND OTHER HIGHLY-ADOPTABLE DOGS DISCLAIMER:
Puppies and other highly-adoptable dogs (small dogs or desirable-breed dogs) at PPA! are very high in demand and usually have several interested adopters. Inquiring about a dog, meeting a dog, and even applying for a dog does not guarantee that you will be able to adopt the dog. 

Only one household will be able to adopt each dog, which means all other interested households will inevitably and unfortunately be disappointed. Please consider this in your search and set your expectations accordingly. Please also consider that adult dogs do not typically have competing adopters, and they need forever homes, too! 

PPA! does not allow the adoption of dogs who are related (e.g., littermates or mom and pup) to the same household for behavioral reasons.

Super social

Enjoys sunshine and fresh air

Walks on leash but learning to walk more calmly



To submit an application to adopt Pancho visit https://nmdr.org/our-dogs/adopt/



 - - - - - -

Prior to being rescued, many of our dogs have experienced minimal socialization. As a result, there is often an adjustment period when learning about life as a family pet. We typically do not adopt dogs to homes with young children. Homes with older children will be considered on an individual basis. Common skills such as house training and leash walking will often take a little extra time. Patience, understanding and a gentle hand are a must. The great news is, most of these dogs come around rather quickly and being a part of their rehabilitation is an extremely rewarding experience. Learn about mill dogs and fill out an application at our website: http://nmdr.org

animal.description:
This smiling girl is Sammy! She has a corgi build and specializes in snuggling on the couch. 

This darling 3 year old also enjoys playing ball, playing with her foster siblings and showing off her tricks. Sammy has been working hard with The Pet Connection to learn to trust people again and slow introductions are important. Don't worry though, once she gets to know you she will be your new furry sidekick. 

Sammy is house broken and does wonderfully in the kennel if needed. She thinks cats are interesting and believes they should also play chase. She loves dogs of all sizes and has exceptional manners when playing. Sammy would do best in a household with adults only or youth over 16. She is the best girl and her foster Mom tells her she is ABSOLUTELY worth the work to earn her love forever.

If you'd like to meet Sammy, just fill out an application at www.pawsitivetailskc.org and her foster will set that up! Sammy's adoption fee is $150 and she's up to date on vaccines, dewormed, current on flea and heartworm prevention, heartworm negative, spayed and microchipped.

animal.description: From P-nut's Foster Mom: A sweet, older dog who is looking for a human that he can trust. P-nut is very attached to other dogs, no matter what size. He loves to cuddle up next to them and sleep. It took him almost 4 weeks to allow me to pet him. He is very shy and is afraid of any loud noises or sudden movements. He has gained a great amount of confidence since being with me, but will still need a patient and loving owner who will be willing to work with him in order to gain his trust.P-nut is pee pad trained. He is not leash trained and has no idea what to do when on the other end. Therefore I've kept him mostly indoors. He does enjoy going outside on a screened in deck, but only if he is with another dog. Otherwise he will bark until he is let in. P-nut hates being in a crate, but there is no reason to crate him, as he is non-destructive. He had extensive dental work done on Jan 14 and I believe this has contributed to his well being and improved mood. He has a wonderful appetite and is not fussy. P-nut loves car rides and will usually sit quietly in the back seat. He is not a `yapper` but will alert bark if something is going on in the yard. He is also quite an architect when it comes to constructing his own place to sleep. He will whirl and twirl, trying to get the covers just right, until he finally settles down to nap. This is a sweet little dog who has come a long way while he has been in my home. He is stil very shy, but gets braver and more confident each day. If you are patient and willing to work with him, I believe that he will soon forget the bad memories of his earlier life and will love and reward you for years to come.Thank you for considering a shelter dog!The Haywood County Animal Services Adoption Center is located at 453 Jones Cove Road, Clyde, NC 28721. Hours of operation are Monday - Friday 12pm - 5pm and Saturday 12pm - 4pm. Closed Sundays. Contact the Adoption Center directly at 828-456-5338 ext. 2 or send an email to adoptapet@haywoodcountync.gov.

animal.description:
Do you love the sound of a piano being played? So does Pedro. This dapper, musical gentleman was born a bit of a ramblin’ man. But now he’s doing the best he can to settle down and find a relaxing home all his own. In fact, he spent some time in a foster home with an accomplished pianist and discovered that the one thing he loves more than friendly people are friendly people who play and listen to music!

This perfectly-sized boy with his copper-colored coat and origami ears is a real lovebug and likely to be the hit of your social media feed (if you’re one of those people who can’t help posting adorable photos of your adopted dog all day long.) Pedro is the ultimate couch cuddler and also enjoys sniffing his heart out in the yard or on short, brisk walks. 

Similar to a young gentleman who spent his 20s wandering freely through the deserts of the southwest or mountains of Appalachia fine-tuning his survival skills, Pedro is slowly but surely adjusting to life in a home and all the new things that come with it. He’s working on his manners,  learning to be patient, and loves keeping busy with fun food toys, puzzles and games. 

Like a lot of us these days, he can get anxious in certain situations and would really thrive in a loving, mellow home where he can move at his own pace and enjoy life’s simple pleasures. With the right home and circumstances, Pedro might fit in nicely with another canine companion. But he’d be even more thrilled to be your one and only. Cats and little people aren’t likely to be ideal roommates for this once-nomadic boy. But he’s hoping you won’t hold that against him. 

If you’re ready to share your world with a soulful pup looking for love, Pedro is your man. His adoption fee is WAIVED due to a generous donor.

To apply, please fill out this survey: https://forms.gle/xNDgaNpskHm11qoKA

animal.description: Sandy is a super soft, kind gal who looking for her forever human. She loves getting pets and attention and will adoringly look into your eyes as you do so. She seems indifferent to having a dog companion and is the typical Velcro dog, waiting at each door or gate in my home until I return, even if I leave her foster-sibling with her, she's not interested in playing with him. She may be 7, but this gal is young at heart (and body) and has really enjoyed camping and hiking with me on the weekends- sticking her head out the 4Runner window and sleeping all night in the back with me. She's lived most her life outside so is learning the rules on house-training but doing exceptionally well! She will need more training on where to potty, but does best if left in smaller sections of the house. She sleeps all night in the kennel without an accident or peep. She will need some basic "house-rules" training and responds really well to verbal commands and redirection. She's not too big on toys and is really unsure what this game of fetch is, but will happily come to her name, sit, or lay down and is very food motivated. She hasn't chewed a single thing in the home, doesn't appear startled by loud noises, and loves being blow-dried. She walks on a leash really well, but pulls when she wants to sniff something so will need some continued training. She enjoys a comfy seat on the couch and will be your shadow as you walk room to room. She will make a wonderful companion to a person who is ready to open their home to a dog with endless love. I have not had her around kids or cats, she seems afraid of hyper dogs or dogs who want to be in her face immediately, and prefers a gentle introduction.

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Ollie is a 5 month old mastiff mix who will join us from the Kitsap Humane Society. He will be a large dog, currently weighing 45ish pounds, will most likely be in the 90lb range when full grown. While at the shelter he has been stressed by the environment, so he will need a solid decompression time. We will post more info as we get to know him. Due to his breed we will be looking for homes with fenced yards and prefer a canine companion to help show him the world is a wonderful place.

Foster Update:
Ollie is the sweetest puppy in the whole world. He would be super happy being your cuddle buddy and loves to lay on my feet while I'm working. He loves to play, but is an incredibly laid back puppy. He seems to be more of a couch potato than an athlete, but loves to chase my resident dog around, go on walks, and play with stuffies. He adores other dogs and is really good at learning their boundaries and taking cues.
He can be shy in new situations and meeting new people but it doesn't take long for him to get past that and give you love. He does really well in his crate. There is a little whining at first, but he settles down after a few minutes and sleeps through the night. He's picked up that if he needs to use the restroom he just needs to go to the door.
He's very food focused and has picked up on "sit" and "wait" fairly quickly. He is great at sharing treats and toys with my resident dog. He's such a sweet pup with a loving heart, I know he's going to make someone ridiculously happy.

Adoption Info:
Adoption fee is $500 which includes spay/neuter, all core vaccinations, microchip, heartworm test and health certificate. Your adoption fee may be tax deductible as Dog Gone Seattle is a federal 501c3 organization.

Apply online:
www.doggoneseattle.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Salem A223829 

Salem is a 4 year old spayed female who came into the shelter on 1/7 as an owner surrender.  

Handling 1/17: https://youtu.be/RP6l_-r76J4
Handling 1/13: https://youtu.be/jhG-ixJAWnw
Handling video: https://youtu.be/O_p0Ubhg0O0
Leash Test: https://youtu.be/HTIN8ROT50s
Leash Test: https://youtu.be/d5Mjin8gcX4

Salem was a little shell shocked her first day. Salem came in as a chipped stray but was signed over by her owner the same day. Sigh. At least she didn’t have to sit on a long chip hold. She was a bit nervous in kennel and hesitant about leashing. Once outside she was an easy walker and definitely owner searching. Her ankles look banged up and raw and she has a lump on her head that doesn’t seem right (medical is going to check her out). She didn’t seek out affection right away but did let us give her light pets towards the end of our time. She wasn’t interested in treats or toys but did show her knowledge of commands by sitting when asked. Salem started to cry to leave when we were inside and would try to pull towards the exit. How heartbreaking for her to know her people won’t be coming to take her home.

Surrender notes: unable to care for, lived with kids 3-5 years, lived with dogs.

animal.description:
Dudley A223664 

Dudley is a 5 year old neutered male who came into the shelter on 12/31/20 as a stray.  

Handling 1/20: https://youtu.be/777hfnWQs2o
Handling 1/2: https://youtu.be/7igdHTo0C-g
Handling 12/31: https://youtu.be/lNNUR-WbxkY

Dudley is a big boy who should be a lot bigger. This poor pup is sooo skinny. He needs about 20lbs added to his frame. I offered to donate 20lbs from my frame, but unfortunately that’s not how this all works. Dudley was scared to come out of his cage, but eagerly took treats so eventually he learned if he followed the lady with the treats in her pocket he’d get more. Dudley walked ok on leash outside, but he was a little nervous of his new surroundings and it was pretty icy. We went back inside where it was warm and Dudley could have all the treats he wanted. His eyes are irritated and his poor chin looks like it has a little rash. Dudley knows sit and chomps down treats like a champ, complete with mastiffy drool. He’s a little cautious with petting right now but is comfortable enough with you to put his whole snout in your pocket for treats, so we’re pretty sure he’ll come around soon.

Blu is an all around happy boy that came to us when he was picked up harassing some neighborhood dogs.  At that time, he was unneutered and heartworm positive.  He has since been neutered and has made friends with some of our dogs in the shelter and is being treated for his heartworms.  If you have existing dogs, we would require a meet and greet with them to make sure they get along. He is a sweet boy that loves to play but also loves to relax.  Come meet Blu!!! Blu is believed to be about 16 months old and he keeps his kennel pretty clean so we think he should be pretty easy to housebreak.  

The standard adoption fee for a puppy or a dog is $200 which includes  rabies vaccination, at least one round of parvo distemper vaccine and spay or neuter.   ARF will adopt to residents who are out of state but will not furnish transportation.  Here are a few of our adoption requirements:  All adopters will be asked to fill out an  application. Adopters must be at least 21 years old. Renters must show proof that they are allowed to have pets, such as a rental agreement. If there is a pet deposit, please show us the receipt that this has been paid. Be prepared to take your pet home with you - bring a leash for all dogs, regardless of age or size (or a pet taxi for small puppies and dogs) and a pet taxi for all kittens and cats. 

Fill out this form if you are interested in adopting a pet from Animal Rescue Foundation. https://docs.google.com/forms/d/10mHOUH71ulyBm-xh0HZcOGsusvXJxrS3pXQHCz3f-tQ/viewform?edit_requested=true

animal.description:
Please welcome sweet Rosie. We believe we came across Rosie when our paths crossed and it was fate. A foster family was looking at all the dogs at ACCT and Rosie was a new arrival that day. We noticed she had very large swollen mammaries and a severe case of mastitis. Three of her mammary glands ruptured and became severely infected due to her previous owners never seeking out medical care for her. Rosie is an example of a dog that was used for breeding and when she was no longer useful throw out. We do not know if Rosie has been shown love or care but it is clear after full examination from our vets that she has suffered abuse. She had a bb gun bullet in her side when we took her in. With a full body x ray review, we found out that she had a healed rib and femur fractures. Looking at Rosie, it is CLEAR that humans have failed her! 

Rosie is sweet and very tolerant with people she trusts. She is a true example of resilience and we can’t wait to give her the life she has always truly deserved. 

Rosie has been doing well around SUBMISSIVE MALE DOGS ONLY!! Rosie is potty trained and is crate trained although she would prefer to sleep in the bed or on your couch. Rosie can be scared meeting new people at first (mostly men) but warms up very quickly. Rosie has not been around children while in foster care so we are unsure of how she would be so a proper meet and greet would be required. Because of this we are recommending children 10 years of age or older for Rosie. Rosie will be spayed prior to adoption. She is already microchipped, up to date on all vaccines, heartworm negative, started on heartworm prevention and flea and tick prevention.

Keagan is a 5 year old neutered male who came into the shelter on 12/29/20 as a stray. 

Handling 1/10: https://youtu.be/LmERjkRuApU
Handling video: https://youtu.be/I6U9tQqPceQ
Leash Test: https://youtu.be/db4YUr8S_bE

Keagan is a happy guy, too skinny, but still very happy. This boy really likes attention too and he has no problem letting everyone know. Keagan can be whiny in his kennel when he sees people or other dogs going out, but who can blame him. He is ecstatic when he realizes it’s his turn and allows quick leashing. Keagan walks nicely in the yard and was overall easy to handle. He demonstrated his knowledge of commands sitting when asked even on the freezing snow. He is under weight and food motivated. Keagan is gentle taking his treats and doesn't push for more even though his belly was empty. He allowed handling all over and didn't hesitate to invade our personal space when given the opportunity. Keagan came in neutered with a microchip, yet his family hasn't come for him. All we want for him is people that will love and care for him like he deserves, that includes regular meals and keeping safe in a warm home. It seems like stating the obvious but it was missing in his recent days.

animal.description:
On a bitter cold windy day, Lionel and Nicole were abandoned outside a local grocery story.  Their rescuer found them huddled together shivering inside a plastic crate with no door.  They were brought to our shelter and are now warm and safe.  Lionel and Nicole are small Rat Terrier/Chihuahua mixes estimated to be two years old.  They are cute as a button and weigh around ten pounds each.  Both pups have been fully vetted and are now healthy, happy, and ready to find a new home.  Lionel and Nicole are quite bonded and will need to be adopted together.  Both are very sweet and friendly and will make wonderful family pets.  Outgoing and playful, these two cuties love people of all sizes.  Lionel and Nicole keep each other well entertained but are open to making new canine friends.  They play very well with other small dogs and don’t mind sharing their toys.  We have not had them around cats, but can test that for you.  We don’t know if they are housetrained but they do prefer going on grass.  A fenced in yard will help with training and keep them safe when outside.  If you are looking for a new family pet, please consider adopting this pair.  Lionel and Nicole are proof that two is better than one.

animal.description:
On a bitter cold windy day, Lionel and Nicole were abandoned outside a local grocery story.  Their rescuer found them huddled together shivering inside a plastic crate with no door.  They were brought to our shelter and are now warm and safe.  Lionel and Nicole are small Rat Terrier/Chihuahua mixes estimated to be two years old.  They are cute as a button and weigh around ten pounds each.  Both pups have been fully vetted and are now healthy, happy, and ready to find a new home.  Lionel and Nicole are quite bonded and will need to be adopted together.  Both are very sweet and friendly and will make wonderful family pets.  Outgoing and playful, these two cuties love people of all sizes.  Lionel and Nicole keep each other well entertained but are open to making new canine friends.  They play very well with other small dogs and don’t mind sharing their toys.  We have not had them around cats, but can test that for you.  We don’t know if they are housetrained but they do prefer going on grass.  A fenced in yard will help with training and keep them safe when outside.  If you are looking for a new family pet, please consider adopting this pair.  Lionel and Nicole are proof that two is better than one.  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Ava and I am a 2-year old German Shepherd. I was dropped off at the shelter after having a litter of puppies. I was so thin and sad. Fortunately, I was rescued and I’m so happy and grateful for the second chance I’ve been given.

A little about me – I absolutely love people, especially kids and I’m super gentle with them. I can be cautious with men but not aggressively.  I love to play with my foster siblings but settle down quickly when it’s time. 

I am house-broken and crate-trained. I was cat tested when I was at the shelter and wasn’t interested in the cats. I was also bird tested with a parrot. He was kind of scary!  My foster mom thinks I’m such a lovely girl and a delight.  I am looking forward to finding my perfect forever home to call my own someday soon. 

During her veterinary exam when she was first rescued, Ava was diagnosed with EPI, a disease that prevents the pancreas from properly absorbing food. She requires  Her condition is easily managed with an enzyme powder sprinkled on her food, so she can get the nutritional value she needs.  With the time, care, nutritious food and exercise that have been provided by her foster mom, Ava is thriving, has gained weight and confidence, and rediscovered her joy of living.

Ava has been spayed, is current on her vaccinations, has tested negative for heartworm and has been microchipped.

We are committed to doing our part to control the spread of the COVID-19 virus. Until life goes back to normal, we will not be doing adoption events at PetSmart. Instead, we will be doing individual meetings by appointment and practicing social distancing at each meeting.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete our online adoption application at www.uaaf.org. For more information, or to schedule an appointment, call/text Kirsty at (435) 671-0985, or email kirsty.ju@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Sweet Lovable 9yo Female 14lbs $150 adoption feePepper is an owner surrender due to her owner passing away. The family member who had her for a while decided he wasnt able to keep her. He said that he had a problem with her pooping in the house. She has been good in foster with just a few accidents, but is highly supervised, crated when not attended , and praised for potting where appropriate. She came to us with horrible ear infections that had been left to get really bad. Both ear canals were so swollen shut the vet could not even get into them to do an exam. After a week on pred they had gone down and medication/ culture done. She is on a second round of meds just to make sure as the vet was concerned because they had gone left untreated for so long. Vet said it may be a chronic issue and its hard to say what long term meds or IF any will be needed, but they look really good now. She is crate trained, rides nicely in the car (crated), and gets along with the other dogs in the house. We have not seen her around cats and children. She is a sweet older girl who likes a soft place to nap and cuddle on the couch or in bed with her person.

This animal is up to date on all shots, dewormed, and spayed/neutered. They have been heartworm tested (negative) and on prevention. The adoption fee is $150.00 If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an application.

animal.description:
**PLEASE ENSURE YOU READ THROUGH LUNA'S ENTIRE BIO - DETAILS ABOUT HOW TO APPLY ARE INLCUDED IN THIS BIO. IF THIS LISTING IS STILL POSTED, SHE IS STILL AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION - THE LISTING WILL BE REMOVED WHEN WE ARE NO LONGER ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS.**

Luna is a 6 year old Husky mix who came to us as an owner surrender because she's not a fan of small children. She is a very sweet girl though and now that she's fully vetted and we've had some time to get to know her - she's ready to find her forever home! 

Luna loves going for walks and playing outside, an active outdoorsy family would be ideal for her. She will not be adopted to a home with young children as she is not comfortable around them but she would do likely okay with older children (12+). Luna is picky about her canine friends - she does get along well with some but can be overbearing with others. On walks she will pull to get towards other dogs so she wears a harness and walks fairly nicely with that. She would do best in a home without cats. 

Luna knows "sit", "shake paw", "high five" and "lay down" and with training, she would love to learn lots more! She has not been crate trained and is okay left alone in the home for short periods. Luna may have a bit of separation anxiety so likely would not do well left for long periods of time alone at home. She loves to go for car rides and is friendly with all the people she meets - she's even great for handling at the vet! 

If you think Luna might just be the perfect companion for you - please head to our website to complete an adoption application. Her adoption fee is $450 and includes up to date vaccines, fecal test and deworming, wellness bloodwork and heartworm test, spay and microchip.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name:Dawson
DOB:12/12/2013
Weight:
Adoption Fee: $375

Hi, I am

Dawson

and I arrived to MN all the way from San Juan, Puerto Rico! I am so excited for 2021 to be the year I find my forever home!

I am happy-go-lucky and I am adjusting so great to my new rescued life. I am a young at heart, early senior! I am a very well balanced dog with fun playful energy but I also enjoy quiet time.
I love to play with toys - whether its fetching small tennis balls or playing tug of war where I let out my ferocious and adorable growls! I love to play bow and my tail is constantly wagging. I love to go on walks and play in the fenced backyard. I love to run up and down the hallways and zoom around the house.
I also like to take naps in my cozy bed and I love lounging around too; I have my own space in the guest bedroom/office. I love to work on treat toys, kongs, greenies and take nice long naps.

I can be a little squirmy and sometimes I use my legs to kick off of my foster parents when I am being held but that is usually because I am so excited and in my past I likely wasn't held very much. But I am really gentle overall and I have started to give kisses. As far as potty training goes, I was a street dog but I have not had any accidents inside the house! But before I was neutered mid-January I would try to mark corners, so my foster Mom kept a really good eye on me! Since being neutered I have tried to lift my leg far less and my foster Mom always catches me and redirects me and it works great! Besides working on that, I am fully potty trained on a schedule.

I am dog friendly but do better with dogs who give me space or that are disinterested and are not bothered by me zooming around. I like dogs more that are my size or not as interested in me. I am cat friendly and I do not mind cats at all. I would do great as a single dog or with a friendly dog my size and energy level.

I am a quiet boy and I would do well in all kinds of home settings! I am really friendly to new people but due to my age, size and history I would do best in a forever home that if there are kids, they are older, respectful kids.

I had some itchiness under my neck when I arrived but that has almost gone away. I also have a small cough but I am on a standard antibiotic to help with that. I also got some dental work done and had some missing teeth prior, so my foster Mom softens my dry food with water and mixes that with canned food and I LOVE it!

I am really excited to find my forever home and I would make a really joyful and loving companion to any person or family. My foster home has a large fenced in backyard that is great for COVID safe meet and greets.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal. Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals! Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept. animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Pearl

DOB: February, 2018

Weight: 50 lbs

Adoption Fee: $375

*Pearl needs to be kept on monthly allergy medication (Apoquel) Depending on the veterinary clinic the monthly price ranges from $100-$200 a month.*

So some things about Pearl is that she needs a place where she can run and play, she loves to run. She gets bored easy sometimes so she needs an active lifestyle. She's good at staying in the yard and comes back when she's told to come back if she goes to far. She is a very smart dog, she knows how to sit and stay out of the kitchen when we eat. She loves belly rubs and likes to follow us around the house.

She is potty trained but only had a couple accidents in the house when she first moved in. She loves to play with all sorts of toys and needs the kind that will last long, if kids toys are left out she may chew them up.

We have 4 kids 11, 7, 3 and 1, Pearl will let them on cuddle with her so she does very well with kids!

She will need slow introductions to anyone new she meets as she can be nervous around new people. Once she gets to know you she's just fine. She is kennel trained and if left alone for long periods she may need to be in one.

She's been allowed to roam free in the house while I am at work. I have security cameras, and she literally just sleeps on the couch all day. Pearl is truly a sweet and playful dog. We also have another dog and they get along great. Pearl really enjoys having an energetic dog playmate, that can keep up with her running and chasing. She is great with puppies.

In the meantime if you have questions or are interested in me, please fill out an adoption application at www.ruffstartrescue.org.

animal.description:
Annabelle came to us emaciated and in rough shape. She has since gained weight and recovered from kennel cough. She has been dewormed and is on heartworm and flea/tick preventive. Annabelle was spayed, microchipped and vaccinated on 1/28/2021.

Annabelle is two years old but still has a lot of puppy play in her. She is very well behaved - she is good about chewing her toys and going outside to potty. She does like to mouth when she plays and, solely for that reason, we are seeking an adopter who does not have young children.

Annabelle has been around another dog of similar size and did very well; she would love a playmate of similar size and age.

Annabelle greatly enjoys peanut butter filled Kongs, her furry Kong bear, tennis balls and chew toys. She is sweet and can be a great cuddler. She does like to mouth during play and will need someone to work with her on some of her manners (as most pups do). She is super smart - she caught on to using the dog door quickly, is a pro at doggy puzzles and loves to work her treat ball.

Annabelle loves to wear her jacket when she heads out for a walk. She is working on loose leash walking (though she zigzags more than she pulls). She will be a wonderful walker with a little patience and training. 

Bully experience is always a plus - (non-electric) fully fenced yard also scores extra points. Must reside in a Pit Bull-friendly city without Breed Specific Legislation (BSL) banning animals that appear to be Pit Bulls.

animal.description:
Cookie is a 2 year old female pomeranian mix. This fluffy girl weighs around 8 lbs. 

Cookie has resource guarding issues. She needs to be in a home with one person or a home that is committed to training through this behavior. 

Cookie needs a home without young children. She also wants her human to be all hers, so other dogs that think they can sit in your lap too are not allowed by Cookie! In a home setting, Cookie is a very affectionate  individual that loves her person. While she may not take up much space physically, she has a big personality. To adopt Cookie, apply at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Tiffany is a very sweet, but very timid, brindle pittie girl who is looking for a calm and patient home. She is very nervous around new things and environments, and is hoping to find a family willing to take everything slow and help her build up her confidence. Tiffany would love to have a male dog friend to play with, but also help show her the ropes in her new home. Tiffany will need a home with a secure, fenced yard, attached to the home as she is still learning how to walk on a leash and isn't fully house-trained. She will potty when loose in our fenced yard, but isn't super confident on a leash yet (flight risk) so having a safe yard will be a key to her success in her new home. Once Tiffany has built some trust in her human friends, she is quite the cuddle bug and will climb right in to your lap for attention. She is also quite the silly and playful girl, and she loves to play with stuffy toys. She is going to be the kind of girl that bonds very strongly with her people and will want to always be where you are. When it comes to kids, we think Tiffany will do best in a home with respectful kids aged 12+ as she will take time to really settle in and adjust. She is not appropriate for cats in the home. 
Have an inquiry? Want to adopt? Please complete our brief online application here and we will email you back ASAP:

animal.description:
Hank is an 8-month-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, 4dx/heartworm tested, and spayed/neutered. This dog is also tested with other dogs, kennel-trained, and housebroken. Hank is higher energy, and good with children over 8 years old. He would also do best in a home with another canine companion. We would love for you to meet this dog and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
PUPDATE 2

Mickey has been with us for a few weeks now and has settled in wonderfully. He’s a really entertaining dog to have around! We took him for a short run and he did pretty well. With just a little practice he could definitely be a good running buddy. He also went for a hike and LOVED all the new sights and smells. I can’t stress enough how good he is in the car—he just curls up and naps til we stop.

Since he’s met a few more dogs, we’ve realized Mickey is dog-selective, meaning he gets along great with some dogs, but others, not so much. He does best with submissive dogs and is not a fan of other dominant dogs. Speaking of “dominant” dogs, while Mick will definitely elect himself leader of your household if you let him, he’s not the kind of dog that challenges you for control every single day. I think he’s actually much more comfortable being a follower, so once he realizes that you’re the boss, he happily falls into line.

Mickey’s leash reactivity is also improving a lot with the prong collar and treats for distraction. When he first got here, he would bark and lunge at any dog he saw. Now we’re down to just whining!

If you’re looking for a dog who’s a solid mix of activity and snuggles, Mickey is your guy!

PUPDATE 1

This is Mickey, aka Mick, Mickelson, or Moose. He's a big goofy guy waiting for his forever home!

Mick is a medium-high energy dude, and he gets about an hour total of walks per day, generally divided into a morning and afternoon walk. During the day, he goes to Dog Dog Daycare (east side of Madison) a few days a week and hangs out at home the rest of the time. As long as he gets sufficient exercise, he's happy to lounge, nap on the couch or in his crate, or play with toys while you're working. When we leave the house, Mickey goes in his crate. He'll whine for a few minutes but calms down quickly, especially if you throw a peanut butter-stuffed Kong in with him. He actually really likes his crate and will go in there on his own just to nap.

Mickey is 100% potty trained! He doesn't have a way to tell you he wants to go out, but he does great on a schedule--he goes out twice a day for walks and then once more before bedtime. He walks very nicely on a leash with a prong collar. He is reactive towards other dogs on walks, but he responds to the prong collar well and we're working on redirecting his attention when he sees another dog. Off leash, he's generally good with other dogs. He's still a puppy at heart and typically wants to play with every dog he meets. He can be a little overwhelming for dogs that don't want to play 24/7! He's possessive of his food towards other dogs so he should be fed separately.

I've never seen him with kids, but I suspect he wouldn't do great with younger kids just because of his size and energy level. Mickey still gets puppy zoomies where he'll charge around the house at top speed--he earned one of his nicknames because he's about as coordinated as a newborn baby moose! He loves all adults he's ever met, inside and outside the house.

Mickey thrives with structure. He's very smart and food-motivated, which makes him lots of fun to train! He knows (and is good at) sit, down and shake. We're working on come and stay. He needs an owner that will be a strong leader, otherwise Mick will decide he's going to be the boss. He doesn't necessarily need an experienced owner, but he probably wouldn't be good for someone with little to no dog experience.

Mickey has been lots of fun to have in our house. He's a great cuddler and is super good in the car. He'll entertain himself with toys--he especially likes bones, puzzle toys, and stuffed toys that he can de-stuff. Are you ready to be his forever home??

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Minne DOB: November 2018 Weight: 66 lbs Adoption Fee: $0

*Minne was diagnosed with Addison's disease and will need to stay on daily medication and her bloodwork monitored for Percorten injections. Depending on the veterinary clinic, we have estimated her monthly veterinary costs to be $300 a month*

Please see attached article for more information on Addison's Disease in dogs. https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/addisons-disease-in-dogs-overview

Hello friends, my name is Minne! I was saved from a very rough situation but I am happily looking to my new future ahead! I am a huge snuggle bug that absolutely adores my people. One of my all-time favorite activities is to cuddle up in front of the warm fireplace.

I'm also a huge fan of toys of all kinds, especially the ones that squeak, those ones are the best! I get a little carried away while playing with toys, they usually end up mangled and torn by the time I am done with them. I enjoy playing ball too and am currently working on "drop it" when I bring it back to you. Some of the super fun tricks that I already know are; sit, stay, lay down & shake! I'm working really hard on a few other manners, like walking on a leash and not jumping up on you when I am excited or playing. I'm a quick learner though and extremely eager to please, so I know I can master both in no time! I currently walk best with a gentle leader, rather than a regular leash or harness. I am extremely motivated by treats and toys, which makes teaching me new tricks a breeze! I'm an active girl that has a lot of energy to burn off. I love going on walks and spending time outside doing zoomies around the yard! I would love a home with a fenced yard so I know that I'll always have somewhere to run and play. I like to find sticks and other objects to chew on while I'm outside, so be sure to keep an eye on me! I don't even mind this chilly weather we've had, just throw a sweater on to keep me warm and I'm good to go!

I am great in my kennel when you are away from home, I will even go in on command. However, if you are home, I just want to spend time hanging out with you and I will make sure you are aware of that. If I must be kenneled while you are home, melatonin and a blanket over the kennel help me stay calm. I am rocking the whole potty-training thing; I just need you to keep me on a consistent schedule so I don't have a slip-up. I occasionally might have an accident in the house or in my kennel but I'm continuing to work very hard on it. I've even learned how to signal that I need to go out by doing circles by the door or pawing at the door.

I love my humans so much that sometimes I will guard them when other dogs are around. My foster family thinks some of these behaviors might be anxiety from my past and are hopeful that with time I will overcome them. In fact, a basic obedience class would likely do wonders for some of these behaviors, help me build my confidence, and create a great foundation to form a bond with my new family. Ideally, I would love a home where I can have people all to myself!

In the meantime, if you have questions or are interested in me, please fill out an adoption application at www.ruffstartrescue.org.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal.

Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals!

animal.description:
Apply to adopt at leadrescue.org. We do not adopt out of state. We only adopt in Illinois and within 50 miles of downtown Chicago.

Foster: He looks like he just got groomed. Nails cut. Smells nice.
Me: Has he barked at all? Supposedly that’s why surrendered.
Foster: Because they couldn’t keep up with grooming?
Me: Oh no, because of the barking. But we have had dogs be given up because of grooming or minor things, so I don’t put it past anyone anymore.

This guy was surrendered to the shelter because he “barks too much”. I wish that wasn’t so ambiguous but it’s all what was provided. So that doesn’t tell me why he barks, if he actually barks a lot, what is considered barks too much, is his bark annoying and they just had enough, or did they live in an apartment and people complained about said barking? Do you see how this could be unfair to any dog? They can’t tell you why they were given up so it would be just grand if their owners gave a smidge more info so we don’t have to figure it out ourselves. To be completely honest, even I was hesitant to take him when I heard that. But then I figured two things: let’s get him out of the shelter and see what this barking nonsense is about and if he is a Pomsky, then whoever is adopting already knows they are getting two very vocal breeds. The shelter worker even said, “He’s not barking here.” Ok, so Rooster does have an off button.

And yet again, I am glad we went with our gut.

Rooster is a 1 year old, 20 lb Pomeranian Husky (although he seriously looks like he got the Husky main genes) that lived with cats and kids, but really gets excited to play with other dogs. He is overly friendly and playful and despite being relinquished, we can tell he did live a good life prior. He can’t wait to go outside that he knows how to grab his leash and jumps up in celebration. Imagine being that excited about stepping outside your home. Oh wait, that was quarantine lol. He walks nicely on a leash and is crate trained, barking only to let you know he’s gotta go potty. However he is not super housebroken, being a marker. He had an accident in the house after an hour walk and then hid behind a curtain. So although he knew he shouldn’t have done so, he seemed to feel extreme guilt. But he was just neutered so hoping it will subside. Otherwise best to stock up on dude diapers.

And so far, the only real time he barks, makes a peep, howls, whiney Husky normal sounds, is when he hears regular everyday noise! So your typical DOG.

If you are interested in adopting a dog people assume you got from a breeder, and heck if we know if Rooster actually did, apply at leadrescue.org!

Hi, My name is Aubry. I am a six year old lab mix. My foster dad thinks I am part Heeler because of my great ears and markings. Don't let my white nose fool you, it is not old age, it is my markings. My best years are still ahead of me. I had surgery on my knees a few months back but am now 100% recovered and had no setbacks. Luckily I ended up with a great foster that took me to physical therapy 2-3 times a week for months and I healed up perfectly and don't foresee any future complications. With my new bionic knees I am now able to do all my favorite things again. I really love to play fetch, hike, swim, pretty much anything outside. I am at a point in my life where I am fine with just chilling with my humans or myself. My foster dad says I am the most obedient and well trained foster he has had. I listen extremely well and absolutely love my humans, so much so I prefer to be the only pet in the house. If you are looking for an amazing dog who doesn't need a lot of training, has good manners, listens extremely well and just wants to please her people, check me out. That being said, I need a strong, experienced, confident and kind leader. Aubry would do best in a home without cats or. young. children.You can see more of me and my story on Facebook on my foster's page, Puckett Robertson.

In the meantime if you have questions or are interested in me, please fill out an adoption application at www.ruffstartrescue.org.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Maggie! I'm about 2.5 yrs old and a sweet, lovable super-mutt. I've been with my foster family for a few months after delivering an amazing litter of puppies. I was a rockstar mom and took great care of them. Now I'm spayed and ready to find my forever home. I LOVE going on walks (although I don't really understand leash pressure yet but that's just because I'm SO excited to be outside doing dog stuff, I can't help it!) - smelling all the smells is the best!! I do great when running with my foster dad -- I don't pull and I stick close by. Another bonus is I'm house trained. I'm very responsive when my foster parents say no. But I am vocal, so sometimes when we're cuddling, if you stop, I will tell you to start petting me again! And while we are on the subject of cuddling, I can't get enough of it. Head scratches, belly rubs, even hugs, I love to put my paws on your shoulders so we are nose to nose. What can I say? I'm a lover! I also love my foster brother. Puppy fight club is probably my third favorite thing after walking and cuddling. It took me several weeks to warm up to my foster brother but eventually I realized we were all in the same pack and we've been fast friends ever since. Because I'm slow to warm up, I'll need my family to be patient with me and slow with introductions. I will do best with an older brother who is chill and friendly with other dogs. I've come a long way with my training and there is always room to improve! If you watch my videos you'll see I'm great at waiting for my food until I'm released and recently I've learned how to wait before my foster parents take me on a walk. I don't like being crated but for short periods of time its okay. I really prefer to be able to roam. The adoption fee for all of our dogs is $250.00 + tax and that includes their vaccinations, spay or neuter, rabies and microchip. Our dogs are also heartworm negative (or we will cover their treatment). To start the process please visit our website and fill out the adoption application (www.dfwrescueme.org) and from there the foster family can answer any questions and arrange a time to meet.

animal.description:
Meet Norma!  Norma is a 1-year-old gorgeous Lab mix weighing around 60 lbs.  Norma was surrendered to us along with her 5 siblings because they couldn't manage 6 large dogs. 

Norma is a quiet dog who is good with other non-hyper dogs.  She tested well with our kennel cat, so we don't think she'll give them any problems.  She's good with all adults, but she needs a quiet home without kids that has patience and understands she will need time to blossom.  She will also need a fenced yard.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/ then email Debbie@BigFluffyDogs.com. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

Hi I'm Rufio, 

Rufio was the oldest of the Lost Boys in Peter Pan. Rufio took over leadership duties when Peter Pan left Neverland. It seems to be the same story for me.  

Hi my name is  Rufio. I am 2-3yr and up to date on my shots, neutered, microchipped and am overall healthy. I am a pretty sociable guy and am always up for walks and snuggles. I am very smart having to survive on the streets most of the early stages of my life. I have some scars and road rash but my spirit is still a joyful and happy one. 

I was named after the Lost Boys Rufio. You see I took on duties of spending time with the homeless and made many friends along the way. I knew we were lost and we needed one another to lean on so I kept them company and watched over them. One kind homeless individual thought I deserved a real home so that’s when WTWTA and a partner Rescue Hands to Paws stepped in. It’s been a wild ride for me so far, being a free spirit I didn't want to get caught but eventually I was gently led to them and now I’ve met so many people and pups I realized being in a home aint so bad! Everyone says I’m quite handsome and Ill give you lots of kisses when you show me attention. The staff of WTWTA love my happy trot and gallop. I have quite the playful side to me.   

If you have pets I need to meet them first to ensure we are a good fit. Im a sweet boy but also big and would want a partner who can be sweet like me. I am a young boy at heart so I like to play and run about so a yard with a fence is perfect! I want to feel free and have fun but be secure at the same time.

animal.description:
Geo is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Geo is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~1.5 years 
Weight: ~64lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: No, he will need continued training for this. He has only been left alone for an hour max and did not settle easily/was vocal. Would do best with adopter that can continue training and doesn't have thin walls.
Dog sociability: Friendly with dogs on walks
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Unknown, but we suspect he would do well
Ideal home: Geo is looking for a home that can be dedicated to work on him with his separation anxiety. He will do best in a home that doesn't share walls as he is vocal when left solo. He is heartworm positive and will need to remain on restricted activity for the next ~9 months until he retests negative.

Geo is an overall great dog who just needs a bit of TLC and patience, because he's still a baby at heart. He loves exploring on walks, and doesn't have an aggressive bone on his body. He needs extra patience when getting used to unusual things, such as certain stairways or doorways. With ample treats and his favorite--some turkey deli meat--he is a very quick learner. While he is less energetic because he's on heartworm medication, he still loves to play when given the opportunity. He chills at home during the day but loves to be showered with pets and smooches. XO! He's not much of a snuggler, because he likes to stick to his own. But that does not mean he doesn't love affection. 

Geo is heartworm positive and will be undergoing treatment at our Ellis Veterinary Clinic. OTAT will cover the cost of his treatment until he is heartworm negative. He is currently on the first phase (Doxy) and will require injections on future dates (TBD). He will need remain on restricted exercise for the next ~9 months. For information on the heartworm treatment process, visit: onetail.org/heartworm

Geo's adoption fee is 300. He will be neutered on a future date (2/18/21 at SNIP Society in Joliet) and a 50 refundable neuter deposit will be required. He is up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
Meet JoJo, an approximately 3 month, male, vizsla mix who became a Misfit after being surrendered along with his entire liter at just six weeks of age. It was only a few days after being taken in by his foster parents that he had also tested positive for parvovirus. Jojo is now completely healthy, up to date on all age-appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, heart-worm negative, and micro-chipped!

JoJo is not fully house, or kennel trained yet, but he is slowly starting to learn outside is the best place to use the bathroom. JoJo has already learned how to “sit” and is working on other basic commands. 

JoJo is being fostered with one of his brothers from his liter and loves to play with his liter mate Moose. JoJo loves to be outside and sunbathe in the backyard. JoJo has done well with big dogs and loves to be chased by his big brother Trooper, a 100-pound Dogo Argentino. 

JoJo loves chew toys and hanging outside, but also loves to cuddle with his owner. JoJo loves everyone he meets and is not shy of strangers but loves to be around his owners most. He is not afraid of a game of tug-of-war with dogs 80 pounds heavier than him, but smart enough to know not to mess with their bones. Potty training is going well and JoJo is getting the hang of where to use the bathroom with a little positive reinforcement. JoJo would love to have another dog to play with but will do great in a home with or without pets. 

You can apply to meet / adopt this pet at www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application!

animal.description:
Daisy is a playful, energetic and affectionate dog. She is learning to trust people as she was not properly socialized as a puppy. Daisy is eager to please and quick to learn. She is currently doing one-on-one training to build her confidence and learn to trust people and other dogs. 

 Daisy has learned touch training, how to place and is working on confidence building skills. She gets along great with other dogs, takes cues from them and learns quickly from them. She would do fantastic in a home with another confident dog. She currently goes to Doggie Daycare a couple times a week and does AMAZING! 

She has finished her e-collar training, so her new family must be willing to be trained and follow through with her training. 

The commands she knows using her e-collar:
*Sit/down
*Come when called 
*Stay
*Leash manners 
*Place 
*Leave it 

Her new family will need to be patient and willing to continue to work with her on her confidence. She will do BEST with another confident dog in her new home and an experienced dog owner. 
Older kids only! 

Please apply at PetPromise.org

Columbus, Ohio only

Adoption fee is $300.00

animal.description:
Meet Prince! This handsome Bichon is looking for a home to call his own. Prince is a sweet and laid back guy who is 11 years young. Prince is very much enjoying his golden years ,and enjoys taking life at his own pace! This dashing fellow enjoys a warm bed to snooze on, and likes taking a sun bath in the yard each afternoon. 

Prince has limited sight, and will need some help learning where everything is in his new home. This clever boy picks up patterns quickly and does not take long to adjust to new environments. He can be a bit nervous around new dogs due to his limited vision, and would prefer a home where he can be the one and only pet. 

As a more orderly dog, his ideal home would be a quiet household, full of relaxation, and without a whole lot of hustle and bustle. Because Prince can startle easily, he politely request a home without children. If this gentleman sounds like the sweet senior you have been looking for, then schedule an adoption appointment today.

animal.description:
Shine is a beautiful girl with the prettiest green eyes! She is a very sweet, confident girl who LOVES to run around and play with toys and play with her foster sister.

 She is very energetic, but can also entertain herself with fun toys and quality chews. She loves to be right by your side and cuddle with you after playing. Her  favorite toys are squeaky toys that she can carry around and squeak. She would do best in a fenced in yard. 

She would do best in a home with older children due to her nipping and teething stage right now. She is learning to redirect to a chew toy. 


Shine is looking for an active family who will take her on lots of walks and give her plenty of exercise. She loves taking walks and loves being out and about exploring the outside world! She has done amazing with leash training. 

She LOVES to be outside playing and did great hiking! She is looking for a family to give her  a lot of fun adventures around the city!

She has been to doggie daycare already and LOVED it! She would LOVE to continue to go and get plenty of structured play time.  She would love her new family to enroll her to have a lot of play time with other dogs. 

She is potty trained, but will need consistency to continue her progress. She is crate trained, but does prefer to sleep with her humans. :) 

She is a smart girl and is showing progress each day learning a lot! She is working on her puppy commands and manners.She will need a patient, consistent family to continue her training. 


She will ready for puppy classes when she is adopted. She is a very confident puppy and has a very strong willed personality, so she would do best with an experienced owner who is ready to have an awesome puppy in their lives! 

We HIGHLY encourage obedience/behavior training for all of our pups once adopted into their forever homes. 

If you live an active lifestyle and are ready to bring this lovable girl  into you home, please apply to meet her. 

Please fill out an adoption application at PetPromise.org 


We only adopt out in Columbus, Ohio area only.

If someone is looking for a best friend, Jules is the one! She loves me and follows me around wherever I go. She has jumped up on my lap a few times, but does get scared and jumps back down. She can't bring herself to go outside yet, this Oklahoma girl stands at the door and shivers. Good thing she has good aim on the potty pad. She is looking for a home with another dog to play with. Cats are OK, but they don't like to play much. Because of her history in her early life, she needs a family with patience that will take their time gaining her trust. Jules is a sweetheart who needs to learn how loving families work. Best with older kids who will give her space

*Please note Jules is from a hoarding situation and needs an expreiced adoptivehome, who is able to provide plenty of time and patience as Jules is scared of things that normal pups would not be*

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal. Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals! All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs). Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept. animal.description:
Meet Cowboy!! 

This poor boy came in stray and so very skinny. No owners came forward for him. We estimate him 3-5 years old. A few staff members gave him a bath and he did really well for it! He’ll need many more baths from some urine staining due to neglect ?. 

Cowboy is your classic dog that grew up with no manners. He doesn’t understand that he can’t jump on you with his claws digging into your skin. He doesn’t understand that nipping for fun is bad. Because of this, we require a child free home. Cowboy is SO SWEET. But he just wasn’t taught the proper manners that he should have been. He will need someone willing to put that work in ????

Please bring your dogs and cats for a meet and greet since we don’t have a history on stray dogs. Cats in a hard carrier! 

When you adopt a dog, PLEASE research decompression. This is key to a dog adapting to a home. 



All dogs listed as on HOLD are NOT available for viewing by the public, unless you are their owner. 
Once a dog is no longer on HOLD, it is able to be viewed by the public, participate in meet & greets, and be adopted!

Adoption cost per dog is $99.00 (puppies under 6 months of age are $150.00). The adoption fee includes the following: OH license good for this calendar year, DA2PP, Bordetella vaccine, Heartworm testing, dewormer, and spay/neuter.  Flea treatment will be provided if fleas are noticed.  All dogs will be spayed/neutered and microchipped before leaving the facility.  An e-collar may be purchased for $15.00.  Because most of our dogs were picked up as strays, we have no knowledge of any behavior or health issues.  Stray dogs are held for 72 hours so that the owners have a chance to redeem them. After that time they are vetted and placed up for adoption. We welcome and encourage the cross posting of our dog's pictures to increase adoptions.

animal.description:
Fiona is a beautiful, sweet girl! She is a confident girl who LOVES to run around and play with toys and play with her foster sister. She LOVES all toys! 

 She is very energetic, but can also entertain herself with fun toys and quality chews. She loves to be right by your side and cuddle with you after playing. Her  favorite toys are squeaky toys that she can carry around and squeak. She would do best in a fenced in yard. 

She would do best in a home with older children due to her nipping and teething stage right now. She is learning to redirect to a chew toy. 


Shine is looking for an active family who will take her on lots of walks and give her plenty of exercise. 

She would be an awesome doggie daycare too! 
She is doing is doing well with the potty training process, but will need a consistent, patient family to continue this process. She is crate trained and sleeps well through out the night. 

She is a smart girl and is showing progress each day learning a lot! She is working on her puppy commands and manners.She will need a patient, consistent family to continue her training. 


She will ready for puppy classes when she is adopted. She is a very confident puppy and has a very strong willed personality, so she would do best with an experienced owner who is ready to have an awesome puppy in their lives! 

We HIGHLY encourage obedience/behavior training for all of our pups once adopted into their forever homes. 

If you live an active lifestyle and are ready to bring this lovable girl  into you home, please apply to meet her. 

Please fill out an adoption application at PetPromise.org 


We only adopt out in Columbus, Ohio area only.

animal.description:
LaLa is a loving, gentle, beautiful Bulldog/Staffy mix who is 4 years old and weighs 50 lbs. She was brought to BarkVille's attention by volunteers who knew that LaLa's owners were keeping her chained outside 100% of the time and were breeding her. Thankfully, our volunteers convinced LaLa's owners to surrender LaLa to Rescue so she could have a better life (they wanted money, of course, but LaLa was worth every penny!). She is a friendly, quiet, social girl who has been impressing her foster family with how smart & eager she is to please. She learned to sit, lay down, stay, and give high five's all in one day! She is extremely trainable and does not beg at meal times (she stays quietly in her designated spot while her family eats until they call her). She loves people, other dogs, and is afraid of cats! She is a medium energy, playful girl who is kid friendly, likes wrestling with other dogs, and enjoys relaxing in the house with her people. She has good leash manners, but gets nervous when loud cars or trucks zoom by. It'll take her a little time to get used to the world beyond her chain, but she's getting more and more comfortable everyday. She enjoys going to the farm with her foster family when they ride their horses and she behaves well around the other animals! She is spayed, fully vaccinated, microchipped and is being housebroken & crate trained in her foster home. Her foster family says that LaLa is SUPER AMAZING, that they love her dearly, and that she will be a wonderful, devoted companion for the lucky person/family who adopts her!

Copy & paste this video into your browser to see another cool video of LaLa with her human foster sister!
https://youtu.be/zvtXwk-q034

For more information about LaLa, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt this sweet girl, please submit an application for her at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
Jacque 
4 years
87 lbs
Male
Shepard/Cur Mix 

Hi Im Jacque from Alabama where I have spent the last 2 years in a shelter. I finally got my freedom ride to Buffalo and cant wait to find my forever family. I am very skeptical of new things (there isnt much going on in a shelter) but Im learning how great this world is. I dont mind being in my crate at all, when my foster mom works I sleep in there with the door open. Im a little unsure of men and little kids and might take a little more time warming up to them but I love my foster mom and older foster sister (17). I try to protect them from my scary foster dad, with lots of treat Im learning hes not really scary. My foster mom calls me gentle giant, because I am a big boy but oh so very sweet once I know Im safe. I walk well on a leash and listen pretty good to corrections. Ive only had a couple accidents when I first got in my foster home but since then Ive been very good. I love to give kisses, but be careful my big tail can take out a coffee table when Im excited cause it wags so fast! 

My fosters favorite thing is that I love to be close to them. Snuggling in the teenagers bed while she does her homework is my favorite.

If you are interested in Jacque please apply at https://www.nickelcitycaninerescue.org/adopt-a-dog or message the rescue if you are already pre-approved.

animal.description:
Princess Buttercup
Female
Age: 6 years old
Weight: 49lbs
Breed: Lab/Shepard mix

Hello there! Im Princess Buttercup and Im here to tell you all about how much I love to snuggle and make new friends! I have quickly warmed up to my foster family and fur siblings including both a cat and a dog! As a matter of fact, I enjoy taking naps while snuggling with my humans and even have been fond of snuggling with my fur siblings, as well! I will still need slow introductions to other dogs, but quickly make friends once we get to know one another. I have met children while out and about and did well with them.

I am a very smart young lady who is nearly fully house trained; going potty while leashed can be a challenge at times. I do think once I am fully house trained, I would not need to be crated while you are away as I have proven to be well behaved during my foster moms absence. I would much prefer a fenced in yard allowing me to run around and play freely while also using the restroom privately, but it is not necessary. I also would love to have a fur dog sibling of my very own in my forever home, but I believe I would also thrive just as well without one. I have moderate to low energy with some tricks up my sleeve such as knowing the commands, come and down and am working on sit and stay.

I am quick to make friends with every human and cannot wait to find my perfect forever family!

If you are interested in meeting the sweet, Princess Buttercup, apply to adopt at www.causeforcanines.org Adoption fee is $250
Children must be 5 years old or older
Must be an Ohio resident 25 years old or older

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Henry! I'm a happy, wiggly, and playful boy. I may not have been on this planet long but my life has been full of adventure! I started off as a homeless puppy in Arkansas before I made the long trek here to Anderson in search of a forever home.

After a battle with parvo, I was adopted but unfortunately, it was not a perfect match. I was feeling a bit protective of my stuff and my new family was not prepared to teach me how to share. Hey, what can I say? I'm a full-figured guy committed to staying in shape (round is a shape right?) so obviously, food is going to be important to me. All I ask is that I get a quiet space with no interruptions to enjoy my meals and I'm sure we can be the very best of friends!

I love other dogs, don't care much about cats, and think new human friends are the best! My perfect family will have the time to keep up with my continued training, offer me tons of enrichment, and all the love (and treats) I can handle! Since I am still working on my sharing an adult-only family or family with older kiddos would be best! 

If you think that family sounds like yours then email my friends here at Anderson at info@andersonanimalshelter.org. I would love to meet you!
