Please bring your dog (if you have one), and a martingale collar with a leash, should we move forward.  We recycle theirs for the next dog :)  I have attached a picture of a martingale collar.  If you cannot find one, we do sell them at the daycare for 10-15.  Purchasing one from us allows us to fit it properly and it helps to benefit the rescue.  We carry leashes too, the collar and leash set are 30.  Adoption donations vary depending on the dog's age and medical expenses.  Typically they start at 650 and go up from there.  We realize this is a larger donation, however we have no state funding like shelters do.  That being said, dogs do come to you fully vetted.  They have been fixed, given distemper, bordetella, rabies, heartworm tested, de-wormed, on prevention for heartworm, fleas, ticks, intestinal parasites and microchipped.  Additionally we have paid for the microchip registration for life. 

*Please note we make every effort to have our dogs altered prior to adoption, if we cannot spay/neuter clauses will be in the contract.

*Please come down to the Dog Gone Inn in Manlius to meet us!

Thank you for choosing rescue! 

Don't forget to like us and follow us on Facebook, we get new animals in regularly.

He's a whole lotta dog with a whole lotta love to give to the family who can keep up with him! Let us introduce you to Tank, a dog whose extreme fluffiness can only be matched by his over the top personality! 
Tank embodies all the good and the challenging aspects of a Great Pyrenees. He is loyal, intelligent, and watchful. He is impossibly affectionate (sometimes too much so) with the people he views as friends, but he is wary of strangers and takes a considerable amount of time and an appropriate approach to be comfortable with new people. Once you’re in Tank's inner circle, you have a friend for life. However, it will take time, patience, and care to get there.

Tank has been a guest in our Behavior Program Manager’s home for the last few weeks and she will be working directly with Tank’s potential adopters to help them build a bond with Tank prior to his going home and will assist with the introduction process to his new environment. 

Tank will need to be adopted into an adult-only, single-family home with a fenced yard and no other pets. 

If you think you are ready for a plus-sized boy with a heart of gold and enough energy to power a city block then email: asalis@andersonanimalshelter to speak directly with our Behavior Program Manager and discuss the steps needed to make Tank your next best friend!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Cinder

DOB: 02/26/2020

Weight: 26 Pounds

Adoption Fee: 450.00

Cinder loves to jump up on your lap and snuggle. She likes to play with toys, look out the window, follow you around and ask for pets. Her favorite playtime activity is playing fetch with her favorite ball. She loves squeaker toys and chewing on tough toys and bones. She may drag a shoe out to chew but once we tell her no she lets it be

.

She doesn't mind being on a leash but is still learning leash manners. She may need some obedience training so she doesn't wrap the leash around you. She can get a little hyper but is just so excited to play and explore. She loves outside time! Cinder has a lot of energy, but can settle and give the best cuddles! We would recommend a home with a nice yard for her to play in and an adopter who will take her on a lot of walks!

She's making great progress with crate training and after a bit settles in and is quiet. She can sleep in her crate or out of her crate just fine. She is working on potty training and does well but does have some accidents, luckily she does know how to use a potty pad for the most part.

Unknown with cats and has been reactive towards dogs lately, at first seemed interested but now barks so she may not be completely dog friendly. Slow intros, training and socializing will help. For the most part she is quiet but at times she can hear or see things outside and will bark for awhile, so an apartment or shared walls might not be best. She is not good with young children so she needs a home that does not and will not have kids living with her. She is an absolute sweetheart who just wants to be by you and be your best buddy!

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal.

Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals!

All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs).

Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept.

Ruff Start Rescue Adoption Policies: http://www.ruffstartrescue.org/info/display?PageID=11744

animal.description:
I'm Grommet, a sturdy 7-year-old Rattie mix who weighs 20 lbs. My foster mom says I'm a true gentleman. I love hearing that because when I first got here I was so confused. I had people that I loved, but they left me at a shelter because they said I bit their kid. You see, he kept bothering me when I was trying to rest. I tried telling him to stop. I gave him a look, then a growl, but he ignored my pleas, so I guess I must have put some teeth into my next request with a nip. And that was that!! I really want to be a good boy. My foster mom told me that I need people who 'know how to read dog signals' and 'can respect a dog's need to sleep without being bothered.' Now, that doesn't describe most kids, but I hope it describes you because I think you would like my gentlemanly manners. I use a dog door to do my business outside (and also to spend time sniffing around my fenced backyard). I share my toys with my fur siblings. I'm a good eater, and I sleep quietly through the night, either in my crate or in my humans' bed under the covers. I don't bark except to announce deliveries at the door. I know 'sit' and 'go find a toy,' and I'm ready to learn more. I don't need tons of exercise, but a little neighborhood walk is nice, as long as you let me do a lot of sniffing and not so much walking. Oh, and I really like belly rubs and taking naps in the sunshine. I'm Grommet and I want to belong again! Maybe we belong together, you and I? Check out more photos of me at https://imageevent.com/newrattitude/grommet .
Our adoption fee is $175 for adult dogs or $225 for puppies under 6 months old.

If you are interested in adopting this dog,
PLEASE READ THE DETAILED ADOPTION PROCESS information on our website
at www.
NewRattitude.org/adopt/

From there, you can access our adoption application or contact our Adoption Team for more info.

animal.description:
Name: Spott
Age: 4 years
Gender: Female
Breed: Border Collie/Springer Spaniel
Weight: 30 lbs.
Dog friendly: yes
Cat friendly: testing available upon request
Child friendly: yes, respectful older school-aged children aged 8+ years, please
House trained: yes
Crate trained: yes
Energy level: low
Temperament: timid, sweet
Requirements: Not apartment appropriate, resident dogs must be similar in size or smaller and have a mild temperament
Adoption Fee: $375+tax

To adopt, go to: www.mendingspirits.org/apply-to-adopt.html

From the Foster Family: Have you ever wanted to be a HERO? Well, this is your chance! This sweet, lovely young lady needs a home where she can learn what it's like to be loved by humans. She has a sad story that can absolutely have a happy ending! Spott was brought to a rescue in Alabama when her owner died. She arrived with 3 other dogs, where they lived outside and had little to no human interaction. While in Alabama she was temporarily fostered in a home with two other resident dogs. She currently lives with two adults and four older, respectful children who understand her story and are working on gaining her trust. A few things about this beautiful pup. She is very timid, she finds comfort laying on doggie beds, the couch or in corners. She lets all of us pet her but she will shake a little until she gets comfortable. Once she's feeling good, she'll give you a tail wag and even a few kisses to show you that she's doing okay. She likes her belly rubbed and gentle petting on her head. Spott has never been on a leash. She was kept in a backyard where she was fed and that was about it. She is slowly learning how to go outside and do her business while on a leash. At first, we had to pick her up and carry her outside but now when she sees the leash she will make her way outside. She has made so much progress in just a few days! Her temp foster in Alabama had a fenced in the back yard and Spott would follow the resident dogs outside to do her business. She has started giving us a sign that she has to go out by whining just a little bit. A fenced-in backyard for Spott would be a plus. We generally leave her food out all day and she eats when she wants to. She typically won't eat when others are around but if you "disappear" for a little bit she will take care of eating her meal. She loves hot dogs and will eat those out of your hand if you're so kind enough to offer! We let her have free reign of the house and at night she sleeps wherever she is most comfortable. We just leave her be at night and she does great. Spott will require a family who will be patient with her and help build her trust with humans. With time, she will be the dog you've always dreamed of!

About Me: Hi, my name is Spott and I'm so happy that my life is about to change! You, humans, are something new to me so I need you to be patient with me and help me learn to trust you. I've never had anyone pet me or walk me or show me affection. I know my foster family is trying to help me to trust and build confidence. You just have to understand that it will take some time. My foster family is very kind to me. I used to hide from them but they always found me and rubbed my belly or pet my head gently so now I trust them more and instead have a few favorite places where I'm most comfortable. I've stopped trying to hide! There are six humans in this house so I do get lots of attention! I'm starting to realize that I can wander around the house without being scared. I was so used to being outside 100% of the time so I'm learning about this thing dogs do, going outside to do their business and then going back into the house. Sometimes I think when they take me outside that they're going to leave me there but they always bring me back inside so that makes me happy! I'm learning to show them that I like affection by giving them occasional kisses and wagging my tail. It's just all so new to me. I have only been around kind humans for a few weeks but I am gaining confidence every day. My commitment to my furever family is that I will keep practicing to be a "dog." Every day I gain more confidence so I know I can get there! I see myself going on long walks, and learning to snuggle with my humans once I know they are going to treat me with kindness. Will you please give me a chance?

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire.

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 
For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Jody, age 2, is an extremely affectionate Jindo dog, who loves being rubbed on her belly. Sitting in your lap is her favorite evening pastime. She is very smart, learning her potty business in 5 days! Retrieving her ball, and respectfully dropping it in front of you for more fun is one of her ways she communicates her happiness. And she is always communicating with her human.
She has had a rough start to her life, coming from S.Korea, but you would never know that from her sweet disposition. She has learned to not react to dogs, but she is not comfortable near them. We would trust her with older children, as long as they are kind and gentle. She is a very special pup! Jody will need a home with a fenced yard and not in an urban environment.

Jody is heartworm positive and undergoing treatment.

Location: Foster home

The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

 We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description: Hello. My name is Nova. I'm looking for my forever home here at the Humane Society of Tampa Bay. animal.description:
So let's be honest, we have all packed on a few pounds during this pandemic. If you're looking to shake those pesky pounds off and get yourself ready for summer then we have the best exercise partner for you! Cash is a boy on the go, go, go and he is looking for a high-energy person who can keep his busy brain and body enriched and happy! 

Whip-smart Cash is working on his basic manners here at Anderson and is ready to take his education to the next level so a commitment to positive reinforcement training is a must. Because this boy has ants in his pants a single-family home with a fenced-in yard would be a perfect fit but he will settle for regular walks, runs, and training instead, if his person can stay committed. 

Cash is housetrained and is a power chewer who loves his nylabones.

Other dogs might be okay if they don't mind Cash's rough and tumble style. A meet and greet at the shelter can ensure a good match! 

If Cash sounds like the boy for you then email us at info@andersonanimalshelter.org to find out how to meet him!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

One ear up and one down lends 3-year-old Spike's sweet face a touch of sass! Filling his fit 70-pound frame with LOVE, he craves the companionship of his foster mom and wants nothing more than to cuddle with her on the couch and cover her in happy doggy kisses. He also loves when she pets his head and ears, showing his appreciation by resting his head on her thigh and even falling asleep on her hand! Very tolerant of her handling him and washing his ears and feet, he's also very fond of butt scratches, Nylabones and chew toys, any and all treats, including vegetables, and is learning to accept both food and treats more gently. Always eager to engage in play with his three large canine foster friends, he greatly enjoys going on walks around the neighborhood, and is at work on pulling less on his leash. Motivated by food and pets, he knows "sit", "down", "crawl", "off", is working on "stay" and on not stealing food. Housetrained, not a fan of felines, and in need of crate training, sweet and sassy Spike will thrive in a loving home with other dogs his own size and adopters to polish his manners, complete his training and keep him mentally and physically satisfied fur-ever.

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet,

the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives!

A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $300. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking

here

.

We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time.

Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

Calling all our herding breed fans! We have a high-energy, unique boy for you! 

Sweetie boy Chance was adopted as a puppy and unfortunately found himself back at the shelter after some unfortunate, aversive training decisions left him with anxiety that his adopters could not handle. Now that his anxiety is being managed and with positive reinforcement, we are seeing our sensitive boy shine! 

Chance is working on relaxation exercises, basic manners, and meeting new people and is now ready for a family of his own. He does have some specific requirements he would like us to share. Chance would do best in an adult-only home or a home with older kids. A single-family home with a fenced-in yard would be ideal but a regular exercise and enrichment plan could make up for the lack of a yard. No other pets please! Chance wants to bask in all your undivided attention! 

For more information or to set up an appointment to meet him please email us at info@andersonanimalshelter.org

animal.description: Hi I'm Bongo!! I'm thankful Alljoy4paws saw how scared and defensive I was at the shelter and knew I was really a good boy and wanted to save me from being killed off the euthanasia list. I proved them right although I needed some decompressing time with my foster who showed me how to trust again.  She says I'm very sweet but very stubborn so I'll need a husky savvy leader to show me the way cuz I love doing things my way but hey, what husky doesn't,  am I right? Haha! I'm a smart boy so it'll be fun to train each other and I really love my freedom so if you've got a big backyard,  I'll be in Heaven running all around but I definitely need a secure yard cuz even though I'll love you like crazy , we are escape artists. I've got a vibrant personality to go with my good looks but even though I'm thinking about lots of stuff,  I'm not very vocal. I do know the sit command and hand/paw command so we've got a little start in training. My foster thinks I'm best with older kids in the house. I have met other dogs and even a horse at the ranch, and I did very well, very friendly non-reactive to any of them. I will bond quickly and feel comfortable around you, I just want what every dog wants, a safe home with lots of love and fun adventures with my family! Are you ready to bring me home? I'm neutered,  vaccinated and chipped and ready for you to love!

animal.description:
Name: Pratt

Age: 4 years

Gender: Female

Breed: Boston Terrier/Jack Russell mix

Weight: 46lb

Dog friendly: Yes

Cat friendly: testing available upon request

Child friendly: Yes, respectful kind children aged 5+ years, please

House trained: Yes

Crate trained: Yes

Energy level: Moderate to low

Temperament: cuddlier, gentle, easy-going

Requirement: Not apartment appropriate

Adoption Fee: $375+tax

To adopt, go to: www.mendingspirits.org/apply-to-adopt.html

From the Foster Family:
Pratt came to us from Alabama where she was forced to breed several times with her last litter of puppies just a few months ago. She is now a retired mommy just looking for a nice forever family to cuddle and play with her. She is the sweetest most gentle dog you will ever meet. When you talk to her, she never stops wagging her tail and has a big smile on her face. She doesn't mind the snow as this was something new for her. She likes playing around in the snow and going for walks. She also loves to chew a bone and play with plush squeaky toys. Her favorite thing to do is cuddle with you on the couch or bed, she absolutely loves to be pet. If you're looking low key dog that knows basic commands and is house trained she is your gal.

About me:
Hello, my name is Pratt. The first few years of my life were spent mothering many puppies as I was a very good mommy. I am really excited to start a new life here up north and I am really liking the snow that is outside. It makes me get the zoomies for a bit, then I like to come inside cuddle up on the couch and take a nice nap. I was so excited to have all of these toys in my new foster family's house as I have never had any of my own. I enjoy playing with my new foster doggy friends and even share my toys with them. I really love it when people talk so sweet to me it makes me get a wiggle butt. I am only dreaming now of a home to call my own with a family I can relax, cuddle and play with. Will you make my dreams come true?

Meet Pepper! Looking for a very loyal, new friend? Pepper is learning to adjust to Shelter life! The living transition has been trying for him. Currently, Pepper is learning to be brave, trusting and confident. In his former home, Pepper was accustomed to his canine siblings and did well with them. Maybe you have a canine friend, that would accept Pepper as their sibling? This fella wants nothing more than to find a very special person and home, in which he can continue to learn and grow. He is certain to be a very loving and loyal new friend!

The following descriptions describe behaviors that were observed during testing and/or veterinary examination: Evaluated for temperament with 335966 (male), and 336121 (female). Did well with both. Pepper is a very shy and timid boy. He is very submissive with other dogs, and humans too. He is very loving, but a slow approach is best with him. He will end up in your lap with gentle approach, and kindness 1/8/2020

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption.

 Primary Color: Black Secondary Color: White Weight: 50.8lbs Age: 1yrs 5mths 3wks Animal has been Neutered

Bear is a beautiful and handsome man. He’s crate and house trained and he does well on the leash! He’s done well with other dogs and would really benefit from a dog that can show him the ropes. Cats are unknown. Bear is pretty scared of new people but he adores HIS people. He’ll need a home that will continue his training when it comes to strangers. Other than that, he’s basically perfect.

animal.description: This sweet girl was seen running the area dragging a leash for about a week. No one could catch her though because she was scared and she was skin and bones. Finally she decided to take cover in a burned out house and a team of volunteers took advantage of that position and were able to rescue her. She was scared but very grateful to get into a warm car and have loving arms surround her. Now she is safe in rescue and is fat and happy. She is a great size at 50# and we think she is around 2 years old so she is out of that pesky puppy chewing stage yet plenty of fun to be had. She will happily go on walks or rides with you or sit beside you on the couch. She will guard her food with other dogs probably because she was starved but you just solve that by feeding your dogs separately if you have another dog. She hasn't met another person or animal she doesn't like. She will make a great addition to almost any family. If you are interested in adopting Christmas you can find the adoption application at funnyfarmrescueranch.org and read all about our TN based rescue and how this whole process works.

Good with dogs: Yes
Good with cats:  Yes - Dog Savvy Cats
Good with kids:  Yes - Older

Available for Adoption: 2/13/2021 (Currently accepting applications).
Applications need to be approved before a meet and greet will be set up for any Fetching Hearts Rescue dogs. 

Sophia is coming to Fetching Hearts Rescue! Meet our latest young lady! Sophia has a gorgeous blonde and white coat and an adorable face that will light up your life! She is a sweet girl looking for a permanent place to call home. Our girl was found as a stray and the ideal adopter will encourage her and help her build her confidence. Sophia loves to play with dogs and children and is indifferent to cats. She loves squeaky toys, tug-o-war, and she can catch a treat in her mouth in mid-air. Sophia is crate trained and walks well on leash. She is still learning her commands, but knows the basics. After all this fun and frolic, Sophia would very much enjoy a nap. This super-friendly dog will follow you around. She is very gentle – loves being cuddled and petted. Searching for a new addition to the family? This is one pup you must meet!

If interested in Sophia, please email to inquire at: SCREENING.FETCHINGHEARTS@GMAIL.COM OR COPY LINK BELOW TO APPLY AND FILL OUT AN APPLICATION: https://www.fetchingheartsrescue.org/adoption-form-online
to fill out an application.

Unless otherwise indicated, all dogs adopted through Fetching Hearts have received the following before being available for adoption:

Thorough veterinary examination.

All routine annual vaccinations, including Rabies, DHLPP, Bordatella (Kennel Cough), Heartworm Test, Fecal Test, Deworming, Microchip, Flea and Tick Prevention and Heartworm Prevention.

Spay/Neuter.
All dogs are quarantined for two weeks outside of the shelter (puppies four weeks) to ensure they don't break with disease.

VETTING NOTE: Fetching Hearts Rescue completely vets our dogs thoroughly to the best of our knowledge based on communication with our Southern Vets. If anything is brought to our attention, we treat the dog. After adopting the dog, you will be responsible for following up with all vetting going forward.

HEARTWORM NOTE: Dogs who were treated for Heartworm can test positive up to 4-6 months after last treatment. All dogs are immediately put on Heartguard/Ivermectin following the treatment to kill the Heartworm larvae. All dogs should be re-tested after 5-6 months from the last Heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
Please read entire post for adoption instructions. Please don’t message volunteers requesting to reserve. Everyone must follow the same process. Thank You! 

It’s time to accept applications for puppy adoptions! We expect to get more amazing apps than we have puppies to go around. The adoption team will begin screening applications based on the order they were received.  Once screened and ready to continue on with the approval, someone will reach out to you in order to move on to the next step.

Once we have enough approved applications, we will set up a time for you to FaceTime with the foster mom to pick your puppy. This will happen by order of approval, so please don’t apply for a specific puppy based on their photos. We cannot guarantee that puppy will be available. If any of the (we will have 4 or 5 pups available) approved adopters change their mind, we will refer back to the applications we have on file.

Due to covid concerns you will not be permitted to visit your puppy prior to adoption day. We will set up appointments to finalize the adoptions and take home your new baby once we know their date of surgery. You must be able to travel to the Girard, Ohio area. 

Be detailed in your answers on your application and follow the instructions on our website. Please be advised that if your screen turns gray it means you did not complete the application and it will not be delivered.  Scroll through the gray screen. It will tell you exactly which section(s) you left blank and allow you to fix it.  This is your opportunity to describe what type of home you can provide. We will be looking for homes that are prepared for a puppy and have veterinary and training resources lined up. 

Home ownership is required and we do call your vet to verify resident dogs are current on all core vaccines and flea, tick and heartworm prevention, as well all of your pets must be altered.

Please be patient. Please be kind.  We want the best possible homes for these babies and that will take time to go through all of the applications and will require some hard decisions.

This process will take weeks as we won’t finalize their adoptions until they are at LEAST 8 weeks old.

https://www.apaprescue.com/pre-adoption-application

——————————
Te adoption donation for a puppy is $250.  Submitting an application does not guarantee approval of application or adoption of any puppy.

animal.description:
Bronco is the best boy! He is sweet, snuggly, and so very playful! In his foster home he is proving that he has beauty AND brains. He is learning basic commands quickly, he's nearly housebroken, and it only took a few days to learn that he gets lots more treats if he keeps all four paws on the floor. This hunk is going to be a breeze to train!

Bronco came to HFE as a Christmas puppy that got too big, too fast. This lovable dude comes in at over 25 pounds at only 13 weeks old. He could be a big guy when he is full grown! He loves to play tug, chase a flirt pole, and chew on benebones. It is important that his forever family is active so that he can continue to use his energy in a positive way. He could make an excellent running partner or frisbee fan. 

Bronco lives in a home with lots of siblings-he is enjoying his dog brother and sisters, as well as his 8 year old human foster brother. He would love a home with kids of his own, but even a home without human kids would be fine, as long as he has a playful dog sister to bond with. 

This guy is truly one of a kind. He is going to make a lucky family very happy!

Bronco's new home MUST be one with a physically fenced yard. Homes with no fence or with electronic fences will not be considered. No exceptions. Please do not inquire or apply for Bronco if you do not have a physically fenced yard. Your inquiries will not be considered.

We do not adopt out of the country, out of the state, or more than an hour outside of Metro-Detroit.

animal.description:
Needs • Securely Fenced yard • No Cats.

Izzy is a beautiful, loyal and adoring companion.  Izzy is a 2 year old 45 lb English Setter/Spaniel mix with a beautiful silky coat and adoring gaze.  True to her breed, she’s affectionate and joyful.  She loves being with humans, and despite her size, will try to curl up in your lap.  She’s also incredibly playful.  Izzy will chase a ball all day long and never grow tired of the game.  She loves toys and anyone that will play tug of war with her.  This active girl needs a home where she can have plenty of outdoor space to run around.

Izzy is house trained with regular outdoor breaks and sleeps through the night in her crate.  Like most setters, she needs to sniff everything, but she’s been easily dissuaded from jumping up to pull morsels off of the countertop.  Eager to please and very intelligent, Izzy takes direction and redirection nicely and is quickly learning voice commands. She does well with other dogs and is suited to be with children.  She is currently jumping up for joy when she sees new humans, but is quickly learning that it’s not polite!  Izzy really loves being with her people, so she would do well in a house where someone is home for most or all of the day.  She settles into her crate when her foster family is ready for bed.  During the day, she prefers to lay at the feet of someone whose Zoom calls and keyboard strokes can gently lull her to sleep.  She just melts when you pet her and gives the sweetest hugs.  

Izzy needs a family who will be diligent about training her and getting her outside to play.  


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description:
We are no longer accepting applications for Toby

Animal Profile: Toby is a 5-year-old medium mixed breed (such a soft coat!) who is a great size at 35 lbs. He can be a little shy around new people, but he's very sweet and gentle once he warms up to you. Toby is crate trained and house trained, and is learning things like sit, stay, place, crate, and more in his Seattle-area foster home. His leash manners are improving and he's a great running partner, but he needs work on his leash reactivity around other dogs and small furries. Toby will benefit from slow introductions to other dogs, and does best with dogs that are bigger than he is. Once he's comfortable with other dogs, hanging out with them helps him become more confident. Toby does have some prey drive, so a home without cats or other small pets is needed. We are only considering single family residence's for Toby at this time. This sweet pup is ready for his forever home, where he can explore the world in good company and have a loving family to cuddle up with. We'll post more information about him as we get to know him better.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $475, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, and heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was rescued from euthanasia at a high-kill shelter in California, fostered and adopted in 2018. Returned in 2021 due to divorce and is now in a Seattle-area foster home. He will be available for adoption in Seattle, once evaluated.

I forgot to mention that I love to sit on laps and cuddle too. My foster mom says I'm very easy to love. If you think I would fit into your home, please fill out an application at https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/PAPS/Dog or petsearchpa.org.

animal.description:
Meet gorgeous, playful Sarah!

Sarah is a Plott hound mix, aged 2 years. She has a chestnut brindle coat with a white chest. She is not only beautiful, she is also sweet! Sarah loves to play and walks well on a leash. She is looking for a family or best friend with whom to share her life!

Sarah was found in a rural area by an animal control officer. She is receiving the best care here, but she would rather a home of her own. She tested negative for heart worms and is receiving monthly parasite preventatives. She is also fully vaccinated and will be spayed prior to adoption. Please call us at 580-252-7387 or send us a Facebook message, if you would like to meet Sarah!For more information, please email Stephens County Humane Society at schs@att.net, or call us at 580-252-7387 (PETS). Our animals are spayed/neutered, UTD on shots, and treated for ticks, & fleas. Cats are tested for FeLV & FIV; and dogs are tested for heart worms.

Normal adoption fee for cats is $75.00; and $100.00 for dogs, but we frequently have specials running and/or animals who have had their adoption fee sponsored, so ... call us! Let us help you find your next fur-baby!

animal.description:
Breed: Treeing Walker Coonhound
Sex: Male
DOB: ~01/22/2017
Weight: 40 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Happy-Go-Lucky, Social, Playful, Goofy, Talkative
History: Transferred from another shelter
Good With: Dogs, Kids
Ideal Home: Active home. No apartments.
Fence Requirements: Required
Special Info: Adopter must do research on this breed to ensure good fit!

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
HEY THERE DO YOU WANT TO BE MY BUDDY? My name is Trooper and I am a one year old pitbull boxer mix who is ready for anything! I am ready to find my furever home with some preferably active hoomans. I have LOTS OF ENERGY and would love to go on walks and runs and hikes and adventures. Can you come with me? Or can I come with you? As you can tell, I like treats, exploring, adventuring, toys, and a lot more. Did I say treats? I will DO ANYTHING for a treat. I really, really, really love food so a home without young kids would be best for me.

I still need to be tested with other dogs. Also, please don't have a cat.. I think they're fun to chase, I haven't caught one yet.. but it's probably best if I'm in a house without one!All cats and dogs adopted from the Chequamegon Humane Association are spayed or neutered, up-to-date on age appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, and microchipped. Dogs are tested for heartworm and cats are tested for FeLV/FIV (results negative unless otherwise noted). A tax-deductible adoption fee of $150 is required for adult dogs, puppies are $200, and dogs over the age of 10 are $85. Adult cat adoption fees are $50, kittens under one year are $90, and cats over the age of 10 are $35.
